When the Obama Presidential Center opens on the South Side of Chicago, it will house the newest branch of the @chicagopubliclibrary.

The library branch will feature a @youmediachicago lab, empowering teens across the city to explore their passions and enhance their skills through music, art, and science. It will also boast a specialized collection that celebrates the life and legacy of President @BarackObama.

node.text:
Over the holiday weekend, five @MBK_Alliance youth from the South Side of Chicago traveled to Big Sky, Montana, to shadow industry professionals to see what it takes to run a live broadcast of a premier golf event like #TheMatch. They even got the chance to meet Tom Brady, Aaron Rodgers, Phil Mickelson, and Bryson DeChambeau!

Too often, young people of color are faced with persistent opportunity gaps, hindering their ability to gain unique industry skills and make important connections to advance their future careers. That’s why we’re especially grateful to Turner Sports for making this exciting experience possible for these young men.

node.title: MBK Youth Attend The Match in Montana

node.text:
After a tough year and half of teaching through a pandemic, South Shore High School educator Monique Thorpe was overjoyed to get a surprise phone call from President @BarackObama. She even introduced him to her 90-year-old mother.

Following their chat, the President surprised Ms. Thorpe’s students with a virtual class drop-in. Together they discussed the Obama Presidential Center and the ways in which the Center will benefit young people across Chicago.

Hear their reflections on fatherhood with @BarackObama and @AndersonCooper.

"I’m excited about the impact that the Obama Presidential Center can have on the South Side of Chicago. I think about how can we, as small business owners, be a part of this?” —Eric Williams, owner of @TheSilverRoom

Get a glimpse into @BarackObama’s recent conversation with @i_know_eric, as they discuss the economic benefits of the Center, their collective hopes for the neighborhood, and Eric’s newest South Side venture.

node.title: President Obama meets with South Side Chicago business owner Eric Williams

node.text: Every #PrideMonth, we reflect on the significant progress that has been made on the long road towards equality for LGBTQ Americans. A seminal moment in that journey happened in June 2015 when the U.S. Supreme Court handed down a landmark decision that legalized same-sex marriage. With that ruling, love won—same-sex marriage bans across the country were struck down.

Sports can be transformative in young people’s lives—giving them space to express themselves and be part of something bigger. Someone who believes in the power of sports is @SouthSide_WolfPack Coach Ernest Radcliffe.

During a recent call, Coach Radcliffe invited President @BarackObama to stop by one of their practices in Jackson Park—the future home of the Obama Presidential Center. Eager to see the team in action, the President made a surprise visit earlier this week.

To mark #InternationalMuseumDay, we’re giving audiences a closer look at our plans for the Obama Presidential Center and how we’re reimagining what a twenty-first century museum looks like. 

A key part of our work is identifying artifacts for inclusion in the Museum. In keeping with President and Mrs. Obama’s belief that change happens from the bottom up, we’ve hosted community collection events in Chicago, Iowa, and Hawaiʻi to discover some of the objects that will inform the Museum’s collection and hear the stories of the people who held onto them.

In this video you can hear directly from Chicagoans who came out to Stony Island Arts Bank on the South Side and shared their stories of the Obamas that date back long before their time in the White House. #IMD2021

After learning about @openbooksltd's work to bridge the literacy gap in Chicago, Curtis Shaw Flagg decided to get involved by volunteering his time to help the Chicago-based nonprofit reach even more youth.

Years later, @curtisshawflagg now manages Open Books’ partnerships with other organizations, ensuring young Chicagoans—especially on the South and West Sides—have access to culturally-diverse books, creative literacy programs, and the mentorship they need to reach their full potential.

“Once I saw the severity of the literacy gap in Chicago, I wanted to help create real access to books,” Curtis explained. “Getting books in the hands of children and families, helping build home libraries—it really changes the trajectory of their lives and their future career possibilities, and their love and joy for learning.”

This #WorldLiteracyDay, follow @openbooksltd to learn more about their inspiring work.

Hurricane Ida has left millions of families without power and shelter. The powerful storm hit southeastern Louisiana on Sunday, the 16th anniversary of Hurricane Katrina. 

Here at the Obama Foundation, we’re thinking of all the people and communities that have been affected by intense natural disasters like these. We saw in the aftermath of Hurricane Katrina how crucial local leaders are to recovery and rebuilding efforts. As the storm brings flash floods to Mississippi and Tennessee, we hope you’ll find ways to help those on the ground.

Find resources by visiting the link in our bio.

Happy 105th birthday, @nationalparkservice!

To celebrate, check out a story that was partially made possible by the Obama administration’s efforts to expand federally-protected lands and waters—and all the work the Park Service does to maintain them: 

When coral reef fish expert Richard Pyle went on an expedition to the Northwestern Hawaiian Islands—a cluster of tiny islands and surrounding area that the Obama administration would go on to make the largest protected marine area on Earth—he spotted what he assumed was a common pink fish until he noticed a spot on its back that resembled the Obama campaign rising sun logo.

What started as a joke about naming this newly discovered species of fish after President Obama quickly became a visit to Midway Atoll to ask for his permission to do just that. To Richard, the Tosanoides obama species name is “something that [President Obama] legitimately earned by his actions in protecting the only place on Earth where the species can be found.”

“It’s a native Hawaiian fish named after our native Hawaiian president,” Richard explained. “We just felt it was appropriate.”

Hope—a deep belief in the power of people working together to determine their own destiny—has always been at the heart of President Obama’s story and our work as a Foundation. In 2020, our hope was profoundly tested by COVID-19, by racial injustice, by uncertainty, and unrest. But it’s during these tough times when we need hope the most.

That’s why last year, hope led the way. Just as it always has. Our 2020 annual report is now out. Read it in full, including a special message from President Obama, by visiting the link in our bio.
